April 30, 2026
1 A BILL TO BE ENTITLED
2 AN ACT TO IMPROVE THE INVOLUNTARY COMMITMENT PROCESS AND
3 INCREASE PUBLIC SAFETY AND TO IMPLEMENT AN INPATIENT CAPACITY
4 RESTORATION PROGRAM.
5 Whereas, the House Select Committee on Involuntary Commitment and Public Safety
6 met six times during the 2025 to 2026 biennium, conducted meaningful work and engaged in
7 productive discussion; and
8 Whereas, the House Select Committee on Involuntary Commitment and Public Safety
9 identified several areas needing further study and has made recommendations; Now, therefore,
10 The General Assembly of North Carolina enacts:
11
12 IMPROVE DATA COLLECTION AND FURTHER STUDY
13 SECTION 1.(a) The North Carolina Collaboratory (Collaboratory) shall study
14 relevant statutes, judicial and clinical practices, and available technological resources to identify
15 areas for systemic improvement in the involuntary commitment (IVC) process in the State. This
16 study shall identify existing gaps in the State's current IVC process and shall provide specific
17 recommendations to address or eliminate those gaps and ensure that individuals subject to
18 involuntary commitment receive timely, data-driven, and accessible support. No later than
19 December 1, 2026, the Collaboratory shall submit a progress report on the study, and no later
20 than March 1, 2027, the Collaboratory shall submit a final report on the study, to the Joint
21 Legislative Committee on Health and Human Services on the results of the study, which shall
22 include, at a minimum, all of the following:
23 (1) A comprehensive evaluation of the legal and operational frameworks
24 governing involuntary commitment in the State to provide formal
25 recommendations for systemic improvement. This evaluation shall focus on
26 the following:
27 a. Ensuring that judicial officers receive timely clinical data from
28 examiners to make informed, legally sound decisions regarding an
29 individual's safety and treatment needs.
30 b. Parameters for training judges and magistrates on community-based
31 services, such as Treatment Accountability for Safer Communities
32 (TASC), "Community Treatment" teams, and Forensic Assertive
33 Community Treatment (FACT) teams, to bolster treatment compliance
34 and reduce recidivism.
*H1104-v-4*

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 c. Collaborating with the University of North Carolina School of
2 Government to develop proposed clinical workflows, transport
3 guidance, and bench cards that ensure successful referrals across all
4 agencies.
5 d. The update of electronic examination forms, affidavits, and petitions
6 to capture consistent, high-quality data statewide.
7 e. Strategies to increase data sharing between DHHS and the eCourts
8 system regarding IVC exams and court proceedings, including the
9 feasibility of a public-facing dashboard and necessary State statutory
10 changes.
11 f. The feasibility and potential benefits of granting law enforcement
12 access to IVC court records for the purpose of better informing law
13 enforcement procedures and operations.
14 (2) Any additional information deemed relevant by the Collaboratory to ensure
15 high-quality data collection and data-driven decision making across the
16 involuntary commitment system.
17 SECTION 1.(b) This section is effective when it becomes law.
18
19 PILOT PROGRAM TO USE TELEHEALTH IN JAILS TO COMPLETE IVC FIRST
20 EXAMINATION
21 SECTION 2.(a) The North Carolina Sheriffs' Association (Sheriffs' Association)
22 shall create a proposal for the implementation of a pilot program to utilize telehealth services to
23 conduct first examinations for individuals in custody of county jails. The proposal shall identify
24 jails willing to participate in the program and determine any State funding needed to operate the
25 program.
26 SECTION 2.(b) No later than March 1, 2027, the Sheriffs' Association shall submit
27 the proposal required by subsection (a) of this section to the Joint Legislative Oversight
28 Committee on Justice and Public Safety and the Joint Legislative Oversight Committee on Health
29 and Human Services.
30
31 PLAN TO UTILIZE MOBILE CRISIS UNITS TO COMPLETE IVC FIRST
32 EXAMINATIONS
33 SECTION 3.(a) The Local Management Entities/Managed Care Organizations
34 (LME/MCOs) and the Department of Health and Human Services (DHHS) are directed to
35 develop a plan to use mobile crisis units to enhance the efficiency of the involuntary commitment
36 process. In developing this plan, the LME/MCOs and DHHS shall consult with relevant
37 stakeholders. The plan shall include at least all of the following:
38 (1) The development of a statewide coverage model that uses in-person clinicians
39 or on-call licensed clinicians in mobile crisis units to complete the first
40 examination for involuntary commitment.
41 (2) Recommendations to improve mobile crisis response.
42 (3) An analysis of the funding necessary to implement the plan, including costs
43 associated with training and technology.
44 (4) Any additional information that the LME/MCOs and DHHS deem relevant to
45 improving mobile crisis units.
46 SECTION 3.(b) No later than October 1, 2026, the LME/MCOs and DHHS shall
47 submit a report on the plan as required in subsection (a) of this section to the Joint Legislative
48 Oversight Committee on Health and Human Services and the Fiscal Research Division.
49
50 INCREASED TRAINING FOR INVOLUNTARY COMMITMENT EXAMINERS
Page 2 House Bill 1104-Fourth Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 SECTION 4.(a) The Department of Health and Human Services (DHHS) is directed
2 to evaluate the standardized training program for involuntary commitment examiners for
3 necessary improvements, and to incorporate additional training into the standardized training
4 program for providers who conduct first examinations of individuals in custody of county jails.
5 SECTION 4.(b) No later than December 1, 2026, DHHS shall submit a report on
6 the standardized training program as required in subsection (a) of this section to the Joint
7 Legislative Oversight Committee on Health and Human Services and the Fiscal Research
8 Division.
