10 PLAN TO ADDRESS STAFFING AND BED SHORTAGES IN STATE-OPERATED
11 FACILITIES
12 SECTION 5.(a) The Department of Health and Human Services (DHHS) is directed
13 to develop a plan to address (i) the ongoing shortage of staffed and available behavioral health
14 beds in State-operated facilities for individuals in crisis, (ii) the staffing deficiencies that limit
15 the use of existing behavioral health bed capacity, (iii) potential use of non-State-operated entities
16 or facilities to provide staffing for or leasing to State-operated facilities, and (iv) contracting for
17 behavioral health beds or staffing as supplementary or alternative to State-operated or staffed
18 beds. In developing this plan, DHHS shall consult with interested parties. The plan shall include
19 at least all of the following:
20 (1) An evaluation of current staffing models, hiring and recruitment practices,
21 employee retention strategies, and the use of incentive pools.
22 (2) A review of staffing requirements required by State statute and Joint
23 Commission standards.
24 (3) Any grant opportunities and other funding mechanisms to support behavioral
25 health bed capacity.
26 (4) An assessment of opportunities to utilize nongovernmental facilities or
27 entities, whether nonprofit or for-profit.
28 (5) Any additional information, suggestion, or initiative, DHHS deems relevant
29 to address staffing shortages and the ongoing shortage of available behavioral
30 health beds.
31 SECTION 5.(b) No later than December 1, 2026, DHHS shall submit a report on
32 the plan as required in subsection (a) of this section to the Joint Legislative Oversight Committee
33 on Health and Human Services and the Fiscal Research Division.
34
35 STUDY LACK OF USE OF OUTPATIENT COMMITMENT
36 SECTION 6.(a) The North Carolina Collaboratory (Collaboratory) shall conduct a
37 study on how outpatient commitment may be more effectively used and implemented in the State.
38 In developing this study, the Collaboratory shall consult with relevant stakeholders. The study
39 shall include at least all of the following:
40 (1) A review of State statutes governing outpatient commitment and the
41 identification of any statutory revisions needed to align the State with best
42 practices in other states.
43 (2) An examination of barriers that limit the use or effectiveness of outpatient
44 commitment, including the availability of outpatient commitment services
45 statewide.
46 (3) An assessment of mechanisms currently available to track adherence and
47 monitor compliance, along with proposed methods to strengthen and enhance
48 tracking and monitoring processes.
49 (4) Any additional issues the Collaboratory determines to be relevant to
50 improving the use and effectiveness of outpatient commitment.
