29 IMPLEMENT INPATIENT CAPACITY RESTORATION PROGRAM
30 SECTION 13.(a) G.S. 15A-532 reads as rewritten:
31 "§ 15A-532. Persons authorized to determine conditions for release.
32 Judicial officials may determine conditions for release of persons in proceedings over which
33 they are presiding, in accordance with this Article. Pretrial release of a defendant found to be
34 incapable to proceed is governed by this Article as well as Article 56 of this Chapter."
35 SECTION 13.(b) G.S. 15A-1001 reads as rewritten:
36 "§ 15A-1001. No proceedings when defendant mentally incapacitated; exception.exception;
37 State policy; capacity restoration services; immunity from liability.
38 (a) No person may be tried, convicted, sentenced, or punished for a crime when by reason
39 of mental illness or defect he or she is unable to understand the nature and object of the
40 proceedings against him, him or her, to comprehend his or her own situation in reference to the
41 proceedings, or to assist in his or her defense in a rational or reasonable manner. This condition
42 is hereinafter referred to as "incapacity to proceed."
43 (b) This section does not prevent the court from going forward with any motions which
44 can be handled by counsel without the assistance of the defendant.
45 (c) It is State policy that persons found incapable to proceed should be provided with
46 capacity restoration services whenever feasible and appropriate and that such services should be
47 carried out in as efficient and timely a manner as possible in order to meet the ends of justice for
48 victims, for the public, and for those persons who stand accused of crimes.
49 (d) Unless otherwise specified in this Article, capacity restoration services are directed
50 toward a defendant gaining capacity to stand trial and may include any or all of the following, as
51 applicable and based upon available resources:
House Bill 1104-Fourth Edition Page 17

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (1) Educational instruction regarding the criminal justice system, to include
2 assisting the defendant in understanding his or her role in the proceedings.
3 (2) Psychoeducational instruction regarding the nature of a defendant's diagnosed
4 condition and the resources and coping skills necessary to mitigate capacity
5 deficits caused by the condition.
6 (3) Except as prohibited by G.S. 15A-1010, other mental health treatment or
7 counseling which is medically reasonable and appropriate.
8 (e) No individual, facility, agency, or entity, or officials, staff, and employees of these
9 individuals and entities, responsible for the custody, transportation, examination, admission,
10 management, supervision, instruction, treatment, or release of a defendant under this Article and
11 who is not grossly negligent, is civilly liable, personally or otherwise, for actions or omissions
12 arising from these responsibilities or for the actions or omissions of a defendant. This immunity
13 is in addition to any other legal immunity from liability to which these individuals, facilities,
14 agencies, or entities may be entitled and applies to actions performed in connection with, or
15 arising out of, the custody, transportation, examination, commitment, admission, management,
16 supervision, instruction, treatment, or release of any defendant pursuant to or under the authority
17 of this Article or otherwise."
18 SECTION 13.(c) G.S. 15A-1002 reads as rewritten:
19 "§ 15A-1002. Determination of incapacity to proceed; evidence; temporary commitment;
20 temporary orders.
21 (a) The question of the capacity of the defendant to proceed may be raised at any time on
22 motion by the prosecutor, the defendant, the defense counsel, or the court. The motion shall detail
23 the specific conduct that leads the moving party to question the defendant's capacity to proceed.
24 (b) (1) When the capacity of the defendant to proceed is questioned, the court shall
25 hold a hearing to determine the defendant's capacity to proceed. If an
26 examination is ordered pursuant to subdivision (1a) or (2) of this subsection,
27 the hearing shall be held after the examination. Reasonable notice shall be
28 given to the defendant and prosecutor, and the State and the defendant may
29 introduce evidence.
30 (1a) In the case of a defendant charged with a misdemeanor or felony, the court
31 may appoint one or more impartial medical experts, including forensic
32 evaluators approved under rules of the Commission for Mental Health,
33 Developmental Disabilities, and Substance Abuse Services, to examine the
34 defendant and return a written report describing the present state of the
35 defendant's mental health. Reports so prepared are admissible at the hearing.
36 The court may call any expert so appointed to testify at the hearing with or
37 without the request of either party.
38 (2) At any time in the case of a defendant charged with a felony, the court may
39 order the defendant to a State facility for the mentally ill for observation and
40 treatment for the period, not to exceed 60 days, necessary to determine the
41 defendant's capacity to proceed. If a defendant is ordered to a State facility
42 without first having an examination pursuant to subsection (b)(1a) of this
43 section, the judge shall make a finding that an examination pursuant to this
44 subsection would be more appropriate to determine the defendant's capacity.
45 The sheriff shall return the defendant to the county when notified that the
46 evaluation has been completed. The director of the facility shall direct his
47 report on defendant's condition to the defense attorney and to the clerk of
48 superior court, who shall bring it to the attention of the court. The report is
49 admissible at the hearing.
50 (3) Repealed by Session Laws 1989, c. 486, s. 1.
