24 pending or, if the defendant is hospitalized, in the county in which the defendant is
25 hospitalized.proceed, the court shall ensure a record of the determination is transmitted to the
26 National Instant Criminal Background Check System, pursuant to G.S. 14-409.43(a)(5), and
27 further proceed pursuant to G.S. 15A-1003.
28 (b2) Reports made to the court pursuant to this section shall be completed and provided to
29 the court as follows:
30 (1) The report in a case of a defendant charged with a misdemeanor shall be
31 completed and provided to the court no later than 10 days following the
32 completion of the examination for a defendant who was in custody at the time
33 the examination order was entered and no later than 20 days following the
34 completion of the examination for a defendant who was not in custody at the
35 time the examination order was entered.
36 (2) The report in the case of a defendant charged with a felony shall be completed
37 and provided to the court no later than 30 days following the completion of
38 the examination.
39 (3) In cases where the defendant challenges the determination made by the
40 court-ordered examiner or the State facility and the court orders an
41 independent psychiatric examination, that examination and report to the court
42 must be completed within 60 days of the entry of the order by the court.
43 The court may, for good cause shown, extend the time for the provision of the report to the
44 court for up to 30 additional days. The court may renew an extension of time for an additional
45 30 days upon request of the State or the defendant prior to the expiration of the previous
46 extension. In no case shall the court grant extensions totaling more than 120 days beyond the
47 time periods otherwise provided in this subsection.
48 (b3) Any report prepared pursuant to this Article shall include the examiner's opinion
49 whether the defendant is capable or incapable to proceed, to include all relevant observations and
50 findings. If the examiner believes the defendant is not capable to proceed, the report shall further
51 include the following, along with supporting observations and findings:
House Bill 1104-Fourth Edition Page 19

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (1) An opinion concerning the causes of the defendant's mental illness or defect.
2 (2) An opinion whether the defendant is able to gain capacity in the foreseeable
3 future and whether capacity restoration services would likely aid in the
4 defendant gaining capacity. Local evaluators may not make a
5 recommendation of non-restorability.
6 (3) Any recommended treatment or education necessary for the defendant to gain
7 capacity, and the availability of such services, if known.
8 (4) A recommendation of the appropriate clinical setting in which the capacity
9 restoration services may be safely provided to the defendant and any specific
10 treatment needs of the defendant or other factors supporting this
11 recommendation.
12 (5) Any other opinions or recommendations specifically ordered by the court or
13 which the examiner believes necessary for the court's consideration of the
14 defendant's capacity or potential to gain capacity.
15 If the examiner is unable to provide any of the required opinions, recommendations, or
16 findings, the reasons therefore shall be clearly stated in the report. The forensic evaluation may
17 be conducted remotely using video-teleconference which permits two-way audio and video
18 transmission between the defendant and the evaluator, unless the evaluator determines there is a
19 clinical need for an in-person evaluation.
20 (c) The court may make appropriate temporary orders for the confinement or security of
21 the defendant pending the hearing or ruling of the court on the question of the capacity of the
22 defendant to proceed.
23 (d) Any report made to the court pursuant to this section shall be forwarded to the clerk
24 of superior court in a sealed envelope addressed to the attention of a presiding judge, with a
25 covering statement to the clerk of the fact of the examination of the defendant and any conclusion
26 as to whether the defendant has or lacks capacity to proceed. If the defendant is being held in the
27 custody of the sheriff, the clerk shall send a copy of the covering statement to the sheriff. The
28 sheriff and any persons employed by the sheriff shall maintain the copy of the covering statement
29 as a confidential record. A copy of the full report shall be forwarded to defense counsel or to the
30 defendant if he is not represented by counsel. If the question of the defendant's capacity to
31 proceed is raised at any time, a copy of the full report must be forwarded to the district attorney,
32 as provided in G.S. 122C-54(b). Until such report becomes a public record, the full report to the
33 court shall be kept under such conditions as are directed by the court, and its contents shall not
34 be revealed except the report and the relevant confidential information previously ordered
35 released under subdivision (b)(4) of this section shall be released as follows: (i) to clinicians at
36 the program where the defendant is receiving capacity restoration; (ii) to clinicians designated
37 by the Secretary of Health and Human Services, and (iii) as directed by the court. Any report
38 made to the court pursuant to this section shall not be a public record unless introduced into
39 evidence."
40 SECTION 13.(d) G.S. 15A-1003 reads as rewritten:
41 "§ 15A-1003. Referral of incapable defendant for civil commitment proceedings.Procedure
42 upon finding a defendant incapable to proceed.
43 (a) When a defendant is found to be incapable of proceeding, the presiding judge, upon
44 such additional hearing, if any, as he determines to be necessary, shall determine whether there
45 are reasonable grounds to believe the defendant meets the criteria for involuntary commitment
46 under Part 7 of Article 5 of Chapter 122C of the General Statutes. If the presiding judge finds
47 reasonable grounds to believe that the defendant meets the criteria, he shall make findings of fact
48 and issue a custody order in the same manner, upon the same grounds and with the same effect
49 as an order issued by a clerk or magistrate pursuant to G.S. 122C-261. Proceedings thereafter are
50 in accordance with Part 7 of Article 5 of Chapter 122C of the General Statutes. If the defendant
51 was charged with a violent crime, including a crime involving assault with a deadly weapon, the
Page 20 House Bill 1104-Fourth Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 judge's custody order shall require a law-enforcement officer to take the defendant directly to a
2 24-hour facility as described in G.S. 122C-252; G.S. 122C-252, as space is available; and the
3 order must indicate that the defendant was charged with a violent crime and that he was found
4 incapable of proceeding.
5 (a1) Prior to the dismissal of any charges pursuant to G.S. 15A-1008, if the defendant is
6 not subject to an involuntary commitment order issued pursuant to Part 7 of Article 5 of Chapter
7 122C of the General Statutes, the court shall make the determinations and findings required by
8 subsection (a) of this section upon motion of the district attorney.
9 (b) The court may make appropriate orders for the temporary detention of the defendant
10 pending that proceeding.
11 (c) Evidence used at the hearing with regard to capacity to proceed is admissible in the
12 involuntary civil commitment proceedings.
13 (b) When the court finds, pursuant to G.S. 15A-1002, that a defendant is incapable to
14 proceed to trial and that the defendant is reasonably likely to gain capacity to proceed within the
15 foreseeable future, the court shall order the defendant to enroll and participate in a capacity
16 restoration program, as defined in G.S. 122C-256, subject to the following conditions:
17 (1) If the defendant is eligible for pretrial release, enrollment and participation in
18 a community-based capacity restoration program shall be imposed as an
19 additional condition of release, so long as such program is reasonably
20 available based on geographic location, program capacity, and any other
21 relevant factor. Additional conditions may be imposed in the court's discretion
22 pursuant to Article 26 of this Chapter, specifically including the power to
23 place the defendant in the custody of a designated person or organization
24 agreeing to supervise the defendant.
25 (2) If the defendant is held in pretrial custody, the defendant shall be required to
26 enroll and participate in a detention center capacity restoration program, as
27 defined in G.S. 122C-256, if such program is reasonably available.
28 (3) If the court determines that the most clinically appropriate setting for a
29 defendant to receive capacity restoration services is an inpatient setting other
30 than through civil involuntary commitment, then the court may instead order
31 the defendant to enroll in an inpatient-based capacity restoration program, if
32 such program is reasonably available.
33 (4) The court shall specify in its order the duration of the defendant's enrollment,
34 up to a maximum initial term of four months, taking into account the
35 defendant's mental condition, the prognosis for the defendant's ability to gain
36 capacity, the nature of the criminal charges, the nature of the capacity
37 restoration program, and any other relevant factor. The term of a defendant's
38 enrollment period does not include wait times for program entry. The initial
39 term of four months may be extended per G.S. 15A-1007(e).
40 (5) The court shall issue any other orders deemed appropriate to safeguard the
41 defendant and to protect the public, including orders to ensure and provide for
42 the defendant's return for trial in the event the defendant subsequently gains
43 capacity. The court may amend or supplement its orders from time to time as
44 changed conditions require.
45 (c) If no capacity restoration program is reasonably available to the defendant, or if the
46 court finds that the defendant is expected to gain capacity in the foreseeable future without the
47 need for capacity restoration services, or for other good cause shown, the requirement for referral
48 to such program may be waived, but the court shall issue any further orders as appropriate to
49 safeguard the defendant and to protect the public, including orders to ensure and provide for the
50 defendant's return for trial in the event the defendant subsequently gains capacity. The court may
House Bill 1104-Fourth Edition Page 21

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 review and modify the defendant's conditions of release. The court may also determine when a
2 supplemental hearing under G.S. 15A-1007 should be held.
3 (d) If the court finds that the defendant is not reasonably likely to gain capacity to proceed
4 in the foreseeable future, the court shall not order the defendant to receive capacity restoration
5 services but shall instead consider whether dismissal of the charges is required pursuant to
6 G.S. 15A-1008. The court may further determine when a supplemental hearing under
7 G.S. 15A-1007 should be held to review the defendant's condition. The court may review and
8 modify the defendant's conditions of release as appropriate pending further determination
9 pursuant to G.S. 15A-1008 or supplemental hearing.
10 (e) In addition to the requirement provided in subsection (a) of this section, the court at
11 any time after the defendant is found incapable to proceed may determine whether there are
12 reasonable grounds to believe the defendant probably has a mental illness and is either (i)
13 dangerous to self or others as defined under G.S. 122C-3 or (ii) in need of treatment in order to
14 prevent further disability or deterioration that would predictably result in dangerousness and
15 therefore meets the criteria for involuntary civil commitment. Based upon such findings, the court
16 may issue a custody order in the same manner and with the same effect as an order issued by a
17 clerk or magistrate pursuant to G.S. 122C-261. Proceedings thereafter are in accordance with
18 Part 7 of Article 5 of Chapter 122C of the General Statutes and subject to the following
19 requirements:
20 (1) Proceedings for involuntary commitment may be initiated on the basis of the
21 report in either the county where the criminal proceedings are pending or, if
22 the defendant is hospitalized, in the county in which the defendant is
23 hospitalized.
24 (2) If the defendant was charged with a violent crime, including a crime involving
25 assault with a deadly weapon, the custody order shall require a law
26 enforcement officer to take the defendant directly to a 24-hour facility as
27 described in G.S. 122C-252 as soon as space is available, and the order must
28 indicate that the defendant was charged with a violent crime and that he or she
29 was found incapable to proceed.
30 (3) The court may make appropriate orders for the temporary detention of the
31 defendant pending the commitment proceedings.
32 (4) The court may set or modify conditions of pretrial release in the event that the
33 defendant is not involuntarily committed, is discharged or released from
34 involuntary commitment, or is involuntarily committed on an outpatient basis.
35 (5) Evidence used at the hearing with regard to capacity to proceed is admissible
36 in the involuntary civil commitment proceedings.
37 (6) Pursuant to G.S. 143B-147, the treatment plan for any defendant involuntarily
38 committed after a finding of incapacity to proceed under this Article shall
39 incorporate methods designed in accordance with best practices to restore the
40 defendant's capacity to proceed for so long as the defendant remains
41 committed pursuant to Chapter 122C of the General Statutes, whether on an
42 inpatient or outpatient basis. However, a defendant's lack of capacity to
43 proceed, standing alone, does not constitute an independent basis for
44 continued civil involuntary commitment."
45 SECTION 13.(e) G.S. 15A-1004 reads as rewritten:
46 "§ 15A-1004. Orders for safeguarding of defendant and return for trial.
47 (a) When a defendant is found to be incapable of proceeding, the trial court must make
48 appropriate orders to safeguard the defendant and to ensure his return for trial in the event that
49 he subsequently becomes capable of proceeding.
50 (b) If the defendant is not placed in the custody of a hospital or other institution in a
51 proceeding for involuntary civil commitment, appropriate orders may include any of the
