19 SECTION 13.(i) Article 56 of Chapter 15A of the General Statutes is amended by
20 adding a new section to read:
21 "§ 15A-1010. Compelled medication for capacity restoration generally prohibited; limited
22 conditions when court may order compelled medication of certain defendants
23 charged with serious felony offenses.
24 (a) Except as authorized under subsection (b) of this section, a defendant found incapable
25 to proceed to trial may not be compelled to take any medication for the purpose of gaining or
26 maintaining capacity.
27 (b) Upon the State's motion or upon the court's own motion, the court may order
28 compelled medication of an uncooperative defendant for purposes of gaining or maintaining
29 capacity to proceed if the court affirmatively finds by clear and convincing evidence all of the
30 following, in writing, based on the particular circumstances presented and specific to the
31 defendant in question:
32 (1) The defendant is charged with a serious offense against the person or property,
33 and there are no apparent special circumstances which lessen the importance
34 of the government's interest in bringing the defendant to trial.
35 (2) The proposed treatment is reasonable and appropriate for the mental health
36 condition of the defendant and its proposed use is consistent with accepted
37 medical standards.
38 (3) The proposed treatment will not cause an unnecessary risk to the defendant's
39 physical or mental health.
40 (4) The proposed treatment is necessary insofar as it is substantially likely to
41 render the defendant competent for trial and less intrusive means would not
42 further this interest.
43 (5) The proposed treatment is substantially unlikely to have side effects that
44 undermine the fairness of the defendant's trial.
45 (c) The administration of any treatment ordered pursuant to this section must be at the
46 direction and under the supervision of a licensed medical professional. However, the proposed
47 course of treatment shall be reviewed and authorized by the court prior to implementation, and
48 the court may impose any other conditions necessary to protect the rights of the defendant and to
49 ensure the safety of others, not inconsistent with accepted medical standards.
50 (d) The court's treatment order may provide for multiple alternative courses of treatment
51 in the discretion of the licensed medical professional treating the defendant, so long as each such
House Bill 1104-Fourth Edition Page 27

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 alternative course of treatment is reviewed by the court and found to meet the requirements of
2 subsection (b) of this section.
3 (e) The court may review and amend previous compelled medication orders upon motion
4 of the district attorney, the defendant's attorney, the court's own motion, or upon notice by the
5 treatment provider to the clerk that a change in the approved course or alternative courses of
6 treatment is warranted.
7 (f) This section does not preclude medical treatment of persons involuntarily committed
8 as authorized under Chapter 122C of the General Statutes or medical treatment authorized under
9 any other provision of law.
10 (g) Treatment ordered pursuant to this section is subject to G.S. 15A-1001(e)."
11 SECTION 13.(j) G.S. 122C-54(b) reads as rewritten:
12 "(b) If an individual is a defendant in a criminal case and a mental examination of the
13 defendant has been ordered by the court as provided in G.S. 15A-1002, the facility shall send the
14 results or the report of the mental examination to the clerk of court, to the district attorney or
15 prosecuting officer, and to the attorney of record for the defendant as provided in
16 G.S. 15A-1002(d). The report shall contain a treatment recommendation, if any, and an opinion
17 as to whether there is a likelihood that the defendant will gain the capacity to proceed.all matters
18 required under G.S. 15A-1002(b3)."
19 SECTION 13.(k) G.S. 122C-256 reads as rewritten:
20 "§ 122C-256. Capacity restoration pilot programs.
21 (a) The following definitions apply in this section:
22 (1) CBCRP. – Community-based capacity restoration program.
23 (2) DCCRP. – Detention center capacity restoration program.
24 (3) IBCRP. – Inpatient-based capacity restoration program.
25 (b) Community-Based Capacity Restoration Program. – The Department or an
26 LME/MCO may contract for three or more CBCRPs. CBCRPs may be county-based or
27 regionally based. If regionally based, a CBCRP shall align with the State-operated psychiatric
28 hospital within closest proximity. The Department may consult with one or more LME/MCOs
29 for the purposes of contracting for CBCRPs under this subsection.
30 (c) Detention Center Capacity Restoration Program. – The Department or an LME/MCO,
31 in consultation and with the consent of relevant sheriffs, may contract for up to three or more
32 DCCRPs. DCCRPs may be county-based or regionally based. All county sheriffs choosing to
33 participate in a regional program must enter into an operational agreement with the sheriff hosting
34 the regional program prior to referring defendants to the program. A regionally based DCCRP
35 shall align with the State-operated psychiatric hospital within closest proximity. The Department
36 may consult with one or more LME/MCOs for the purposes of contracting for DCCRPs under
37 this subsection.
38 (d) Inpatient-Based Capacity Restoration Program. – IBCRPs are programs offered by
39 inpatient psychiatric facilities with the expertise to provide capacity restoration programming.
40 These programs shall be available within the State psychiatric hospital system. Inpatient
41 treatment is intended for defendants that are likely to benefit from inpatient level of care but who
42 may or may not meet involuntary commitment criteria."
43 SECTION 13.(l) The Department of Health and Human Services shall by December
44 1, 2026, adopt guidelines for treatment of individuals who are referred pursuant to
45 G.S. 15A-1003 to a detention center capacity restoration program, community-based capacity
46 restoration program, or inpatient-based capacity restoration program, as defined in
47 G.S. 122C-256, as amended by this act, incorporating best practices to restore the individual's
48 capacity to proceed to trial in criminal court. The adopted guidelines shall be published to the
49 official website of the Department of Health and Human Services.
50 SECTION 13.(m) G.S. 122C-273(a) reads as rewritten:
Page 28 House Bill 1104-Fourth Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 "(a) Unless prohibited by Chapter 90 of the General Statutes, if the commitment order
2 directs outpatient treatment, the outpatient treatment physician may prescribe or administer, or
3 the center may administer, to the respondent reasonable and appropriate medication and
4 treatment that are consistent with accepted medical standards.
5 (1) If the respondent fails to comply or clearly refuses to comply with all or part
6 of the prescribed treatment, the physician, the physician's designee, or the
7 center shall make all reasonable effort to solicit the respondent's compliance.
8 These efforts shall be documented and reported to the court with a request for
9 a supplemental hearing.
10 (2) If the respondent fails to comply, but does not clearly refuse to comply, with
11 all or part of the prescribed treatment after reasonable effort to solicit the
12 respondent's compliance, the physician, the physician's designee, or the center
13 may request the court to order the respondent taken into custody for the
14 purpose of examination. Upon receipt of this request, the clerk shall issue an
15 order to a law-enforcement officer to take the respondent into custody and to
16 take him immediately to the designated outpatient treatment physician or
17 center for examination. The custody order is valid throughout the State. The
18 law-enforcement officer shall turn the respondent over to the custody of the
19 physician or center who shall conduct the examination and then release the
20 respondent. The law-enforcement officer may wait during the examination
21 and return the respondent to his home after the examination. An examination
22 conducted under this subsection in which a physician or eligible psychologist
23 determines that the respondent meets the criteria for inpatient commitment
24 may be substituted for the first examination required by G.S. 122C-263 if the
25 clerk or magistrate issues a custody order within six hours after the
26 examination was performed.
27 (3) In no case may the respondent be physically forced to take medication or
28 forcibly detained for treatment unless he poses an immediate danger to himself
29 or others. In such cases inpatient commitment proceedings shall be initiated.
30 The administration of medication pursuant to court order for a criminal
31 defendant found incapable to proceed to trial is governed by the provisions of
32 G.S. 15A-1010 and not by this section.
33 (4) At any time that the outpatient treatment physician or center finds that the
34 respondent no longer meets the criteria set out in G.S. 122C-263(d)(1), the
35 physician or center shall so notify the court and the case shall be terminated;
36 provided, however, if the respondent was initially committed as a result of
37 conduct resulting in his being charged with a violent crime, including a crime
38 involving an assault with a deadly weapon, and the respondent was found
39 incapable of proceeding, the designated outpatient treatment physician or
40 center shall notify the clerk that discharge is recommended. The clerk shall
41 calendar a supplemental hearing as provided in G.S. 122C-274 to determine
42 whether the respondent meets the criteria for outpatient commitment.
43 (5) Any individual who has knowledge that a respondent on outpatient
44 commitment has become dangerous to himself, as defined by
45 G.S. 122C-3(11)a., and others, as defined in G.S. 122C-3(11)b., may initiate
46 a new petition for inpatient commitment as provided in this Part. If the
47 respondent is committed as an inpatient, the outpatient commitment shall be
48 terminated and notice sent by the clerk of court in the county where the
49 respondent is committed as an inpatient to the clerk of court of the county
50 where the outpatient commitment is being supervised."
